        "source": "U.P.P.C.S. (Mains) 2014",
        "explanation": "The Rigveda, at first sight, reflects polytheism. The Aryans believed in the existence of various gods. Broadly, there were three classes of Vedic deities – 1. deities of the sky, 2. deities of the atmosphere, and 3. deities of the earth. While praising these deities, the Vedic sages regarded whichever deity they were praising at a given time as the chief or supreme deity. This is also called henotheism. Besides this, the Rigveda also supports monotheism by saying, “Ekam sat vipra bahudha vadanti” (Truth is one; the wise speak of it in many ways). In the monotheistic idea of the Rigveda, elements of non-dualism, all-gods doctrine, and polytheism are included. However, this concept of one God in the Vedas is different from the modern form of theism.",
