        "disputed": false,
        "source": "U.P.P.C.S. (Pre) 1999",
        "explanation": "On the basis of inscriptional evidence, it is clear that after adopting Buddhism, Ashoka stopped hunting and pleasure tours and, in their place, began Dharma (Dhamma) tours. In the 10th year after his coronation, as mentioned in the Eighth Rock Edict, he visited Sambodhi (Bodh Gaya), and in the 20th year, as mentioned in the Rummindei inscription, he visited Lumbini and paid homage there. On the basis of Buddhist literary evidence, historian Vincent A. Smith has given the sequence of Ashoka’s Dhamma tours as follows: Lumbini, Kapilavastu, Bodh Gaya, Sarnath, Kushinagar, and Shravasti. Thus, option (d), 4, 2, 1, 5, 3, and 6, is the correct sequence.",
