        "explanation": "During the Sultanate period in India, the Iqta system was introduced by Iltutmish. Under this system, the holder of an Iqta (Iqtadar or Muqti) was entrusted with the responsibility of collecting revenue and taxes from that area. The revenue collected from the Iqta did not go directly into the Sultan’s treasury; rather, the Muqti used it to meet military and administrative expenses, and he had to maintain soldiers for the Sultan’s service out of that revenue. The income from Khalisa land, however, went directly into the Sultan’s treasury. A description of the early Iqta system is found in the Persian book Siyasatnama written by Abu Ali Hasan ibn Ali Tusi, known as Nizam al-Mulk.",
