        "explanation": "The chronological details of the travellers mentioned in the question are as follows— (i) Al-Biruni - Al-Biruni was a resident of Khiva (ancient Khwarizm). He came to India with Mahmud of Ghazni during his invasion of India in the 11th century A.D. (ii) Ibn Battuta - He was a traveller from Morocco (Africa). He came to India during the Sultanate period in the reign of Muhammad bin Tughlaq (1325–1351). Muhammad Tughlaq appointed him as the Qazi of Delhi. Later, in 1342 A.D., he sent him to China as his ambassador. Ibn Battuta described his travel accounts in a book named Rihla. (iii) Tavernier - The French traveller Tavernier visited India during the reign of Shah Jahan. He was a jeweller by profession. Between 1638 and 1663 A.D., he visited India six times. He described his travels in a book titled Travels in India. (iv) Manucci - He was an Italian traveller. At the age of 14, he fled from his hometown Venice and, travelling through Asia Minor and Persia, reached India. He worked as an artilleryman in the service of Prince Dara Shikoh and later adopted the profession of a physician. He wrote a book titled Storia do Mogor, which has been called the Mirror of 17th-century India.",
