        "source": "U.P. R.O./A.R.O. (Mains) 2021",
        "explanation": "Sher Shah Suri (1540–1545 A.D.) occupies an important place among the rulers of medieval India. He was the architect of an excellent administrative system. Because of the reforms introduced by him in the field of administration, he is regarded as the forerunner of Akbar. Hence, statement 1 is true. Sher Shah’s qualities as a ruler were more remarkable than his victories on the battlefield. Although he achieved success in some battles, he also faced failure in others. For example, Humayun defeated the Afghans, at a place called Daurah (Devra). Similarly, Sher Shah’s victory over Marwar was the result of treachery. On the other hand, the works carried out by him as an administrator occupy an important place in history. For example, due to his revenue reforms, the royal exchequer increased. In the field of military reforms, he strictly enforced the practice of branding horses, which had earlier been introduced in India by Alauddin Khalji. He replaced old worn-out coins with pure gold, silver, and copper coins. He introduced the pure silver rupee (178 grains) and the copper dam (380 grains). Likewise, Sher Shah’s judicial system also occupied an unparalleled place in medieval India. Therefore, statement 2 is incorrect.",
