        "answer": [
          "d"
        ],
        "disputed": false,
        "source": "U.P. U.D.A./L.D.A. (Spl) (Mains) 2010 U.P. U.D.A./L.D.A. (Pre) 2010",
        "explanation": "The word mansab means “rank” or “position,” and mansabdar meant an officer who held a rank or grade in the imperial army. There were three categories or classes of mansabdars. The first category included those who maintained a number of cavalrymen equal to their prescribed mansab. The second category included those whose number of cavalrymen was half or more than half of their prescribed mansab. The third category included those whose number of cavalrymen was less than half of the prescribed mansab. Mansabdars were not hereditary officers. They were paid either in cash or in the form of a jagir. Thus, option (d) is the correct answer.",
        "bonus": ""
