        "disputed": false,
        "source": "U.P.P.C.S. (Pre) 1995",
        "explanation": "In medieval India, the chief source of the state’s income was land revenue. During Babur’s reign, all land was distributed in the form of jagirs. Humayun did not undertake any work for land reforms during his reign. Sher Shah made arrangements for a well-organized revenue system, but that system was destroyed after the death of Islam Shah. Akbar was the first Mughal emperor who established the revenue system in a proper manner and developed the best land revenue system of the medieval period. During his reign, generally one-third of the produce was taken as land revenue. In the time of Shah Jahan, land revenue increased to 50 percent. He started the farming system for the collection of land revenue.",
