        "explanation": "As a result of the Treaty of Sugauli (1816), Nepal ceded Kumaon, the eastern part of Garhwal, and some parts of the Terai to the British East India Company. The areas falling under Kumaon came under British rule. Kathmandu: It remained the capital of Nepal; under the treaty, there was only a provision for the appointment of a British Resident, and Kathmandu was not ceded to the British. Shimla: The treaty established British control over the hill belt in which Shimla is located; however, the actual transfer of Shimla town/station took place in 1830 from Keonthal/ Patiala. Ranikhet: Ranikhet is situated in the Kumaon region (present-day Uttarakhand). After the Treaty of Sugauli, Kumaon came under British control. Nainital: Nainital was also a part of Kumaon; when Kumaon came under British control, this region too came under Company rule. Note: In its preliminary answer key, UPPSC gave option (c) as the answer to this question, which is not correct.",
