        "source": "explanation of (A). explanation of (A). U.P.P.C.S. (Pre) 2017",
        "explanation": "According to the nationalist interpretation, the drain of wealth meant the transfer of wealth, property, and goods from India to England without any equivalent economic, commercial, or material return to India. During the British period, India’s balance of trade was generally favourable because exports exceeded imports. The sources of the East India Company’s drain included profits from trade monopoly, salaries and pensions of Company employees, and dividends paid to its investors. The money sent by the Company to England later returned to India in the form of foreign loans and capital investment. However, this investment was meant not for the development of the country but for the maximum exploitation of Indian resources. After 1813, this economic drain assumed the form of unrequited exports. Before 1914, British capital investment in India was made mainly in such sectors as railways, roads, commercial shipping, mineral industries such as coal and gold, and financial institutions such as banks, insurance companies, and financial corporations. These served as complements to British industry and left no scope for Indian industrial development. Dadabhai Naoroji described the drain of wealth as the “evil of all evils” and regarded it as the chief cause of India’s poverty. Therefore, both (A) and (R) are correct, and (R) is the correct explanation of (A).",
