        "source": "U.P.P.C.S. (Pre) 1994",
        "explanation": "The most organized and serious challenge to British supremacy came from the Wahabi Movement. Syed Ahmad Barelvi of Rae Bareli was the pioneer of this movement in India. He was influenced by Abdul Wahab of Arabia, but an even greater influence on him was that of Shah Waliullah, a saint of Delhi. Due to the efforts of Syed Ahmad Barelvi, the ideas of this movement soon spread to Kabul, the North-West Frontier Province, Bengal, Bihar, the Central Provinces, etc. For some time, his followers captured Peshawar in 1830 and issued coins in his name, but he was killed the following year in the Battle of Balakot. After the death of Syed Ahmad Barelvi, Patna became the centre of this movement. During this period, the movement was led by Maulvi Qasim, Vilayat Ali, Inayat Ali, Ahmadullah, etc. Besides Patna, branches of this movement were also established in Hyderabad, Madras, Bengal, the United Provinces, and Bombay. The Wahabis made a significant contribution to the spread of anti-British feeling during the Revolt of 1857.",
