        "explanation": "According to historian Dhananjay Keer’s book 'Lokmanya Tilak–Father of the Indian Freedom Struggle', Bal Gangadhar Tilak and Gopal Ganesh Agarkar were confined in Dongri Jail, Bombay (Mumbai), on 17 July 1882 to serve four months’ imprisonment for their journalistic writings in the newspapers 'Maratha' and 'Kesari'. This was the first occasion on which any Indian was sentenced to imprisonment while performing his duties as a journalist. However, Bipin Chandra and others, in the English edition of their book 'India’s Struggle for Independence', have stated that Surendranath Banerjee was the first Indian to be imprisoned for discharging his duties as a journalist. But Banerjee received this punishment on 2 April 1883 for his editorial published in 'The Bengalee'. Thus, chronologically, Bal Gangadhar Tilak and Gopal Ganesh Agarkar were the first Indians to go to jail for discharging journalistic duties.",
