        "explanation": "Basically, the plan for establishing the Home Rule League was prepared by Annie Besant. The movement for self- rule began with the publication of the weekly journal 'Commonweal' on 2 January 1914. Keeping in view the objective of self-government within the British Empire, this journal adopted religious freedom, national education, and social and political reforms as its basic programme. To carry forward this programme, two separate Home Rule Leagues were established, and both were complementary to each other. In April 1916, Tilak established the Indian Home Rule League, and five months later, in September 1916, Mrs. Annie Besant established the Home Rule League. Tilak’s League was confined to six branches in Karnataka, Maharashtra (excluding Bombay), the Central Provinces, and Berar. The rest of the country was assigned to Annie Besant’s League. Besant’s League had a very loose organization; any three persons could open a branch anywhere, whereas Tilak’s League had a very strong organization, and the functions and areas of all six branches were clearly defined. The two Leagues did not merge because, in Annie Besant’s words, “Some of his supporters did not like me, and some of my supporters did not like him. But there was no quarrel of any kind between him and me.” Thus, there were no differences between Tilak and Besant. r Gandhi and his Early Movements",
