        "explanation": "Mahatma Gandhi began the Satyagraha movement in India from Champaran in Bihar. In Champaran, the farmers were forced by the British to cultivate indigo on 3/20 of their landholding (three kathas in a bigha). This was known as the Tinkathia system. If the farmers refused to cultivate indigo, the British subjected them to severe oppression. In addition, nearly 40 kinds of taxes had been imposed on them. Rajkumar Shukla, a farmer from Bihar, met Gandhiji and appealed to him to free the peasants from British oppression. During Gandhi’s stay in Calcutta, Rajkumar Shukla accompanied him, and in April 1917 Gandhi went to Champaran and started Satyagraha to free the peasants from British exploitation and forced labour. In July 1917, the Champaran Agrarian Committee was formed. Gandhiji was also one of its members. On the basis of this committee’s report, the Tinkathia system was abolished.",
